Topic: Modules & Packages (How Real Projects Work)

üìÖ Date: 06 February 2026
‚è±Ô∏è Duration: ~45 minutes

1Ô∏è‚É£ What is a Module?

A module is simply a Python file (.py) that contains functions, variables, or classes.

Example:

üëâ math is a built-in module.

import math

print(math.sqrt(25))
print(math.pi)
2Ô∏è‚É£ Types of Modules

Built-in (math, random, datetime)

User-defined (your own .py file)

External (pip install)

3Ô∏è‚É£ Importing Modules
Normal Import
import math
print(math.sqrt(16))
Import Specific Function
from math import sqrt
print(sqrt(16))
Rename Module
import math as m
print(m.pi)
4Ô∏è‚É£ Create Your Own Module üî•

Create file: my_module.py

def greet(name):
    return "Hello " + name

def add(a, b):
    return a + b

Now in another file:

import my_module

print(my_module.greet("Akshay"))
print(my_module.add(10, 20))
5Ô∏è‚É£ What is a Package?

A package is a folder containing multiple modules.

Example structure:

project/
    main.py
    utils/
        math_tools.py
        string_tools.py

Folder must contain:

__init__.py

Then you can import like:

from utils import math_tools
üî• Why Modules & Packages Matter?

Used in large projects

Required for scalable systems

Used in ML libraries

Used in backend development

üß† Memory Trick

File = Module

Folder of modules = Package

import ‚Üí use external code
